segments.text: And sort of the same problem is, I'm not sure quite yet, the county organizations feature and explain briefly about, but I really want to just give a composite view of the world, the Texas world.
When I lived in Grandview and was in practice, I was a member of the Tarrant County Veterinary Medical Association.
When I was in Houston, the Harris County.
Then the Harris County group splintered off, and they had the large animal practitioners in Harris County, and they had the Harris County Veterinary Medical Association.
So, you know, somewhere you need to mention that.
I suppose that still exists.
As far as I know, they've done a lot of those county histories, and I've got most of that material, I believe.
I gave a program there eight or ten years ago with a large animal group out on the way somewhere up from Houston.
Let's close, I guess, with this thought.
What are the big, as you see it, trends in veterinary medicine or developing problems in the profession from your perspective, both as a practitioner and as an academician, let's say?
Do you see any radical changes in development?
Or maybe not even radical, but just
Well, I've seen a lot of changes since I've been here.

I think one of the things as a practitioner that I see is the intensification of pursuit of research, publish or perish, and sort of getting away from the trend of training for practitioners entirely.
To me, it seems to concentrate on selecting a person that has
propensity for research and practice.
They may be like they used to.
They may change their attitude after they get to be seniors and graduates.

Do you see the practice changing out in the field such that now you're going to set up increasingly the clinic, the specialized clinic, or the specialists, let's say, and then maybe a few general, fewer general practitioners who feed in their clients to the specialists?
I guess if they're sharp enough to get in and graduate from college of veterinary medicine, they can recognize a need.
If there's a need somewhere and they're not doing too well in a specialty, we're referral practice only.
I think Herman Dietrich's a good example of that.
We're back to more of a general practice.
Worming and inoculations and general health in the patient is still, in my opinion, a moneymaker.
If you've got everybody sending you orthopedic cases and you only do internal fixation orthopedics, you get a fabulous fee.
Certainly you're going to get financially well.
This subject's addressed in this last AVMA journal.
Have you looked at it?
No, I just got yesterday.
I think you need to have a copy of it.
Okay, I'll look at that.
It's in regard to analysis of the Pew report.
Good.
Veterinary medicine is changing in this respect that there's less attention to the individual animal and more concern about herd health and such as that.
I don't accept that statement.
I think this might be true in food animal medicine, but food animal medicine is becoming less and less a part of veterinary medicine all the time.
Say that again?
Food is becoming less and less.
Okay.
Because it's usually herd health or flock health instead of individual animals.
The health of that depends on the diagnosis of the individual diseased animal.
Okay.
So you sit on the fence looking and throw a hundred head out there and say, well, you know, you ought to do this and that.
You've got to still go back.
It's treating the individual animal that is of interest to the practicing veterinarian.
And that is where the money is going to be.
It's becoming more like human health medicine.
And instead of departing from that picture, it's approaching it more, I think.

the value of the individual animal when you're talking about the equine species and the which involves sentiment and emotion as well but that's the pet practice whether it's exotic pets cat and dog it's sentiment and emotion that causes them to spend unlimited sums on these animals
Yeah, and that's one of the big changes, I kind of sense, too.
It's not an economic decision like it was.
I don't know whether I ought to make this statement or not, but it certainly is the basis for a lot of my feelings and philosophy about veterinary medicine.
I think that our administrators are a result of the academic environment more and more.
Less and less of them have had experience as practitioners dealing with
With people and animals in the real world there.
I don't know but what someday we're going to look for our administrators to come out of Administrative training in college.
I wouldn't be surprised.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, I wouldn't be surprised, you know business.
Yeah Education is a business It's not veterinary medicine That's right and the business is
is getting bucks.
How can we get research dollars?
They don't devise something that needs to be researched.
They don't have the objective out there.
No, that's right.
It's the bucks.
Can we get a quarter of a million dollars, and how can we spend it?
And of course, that's typical of the whole world, not just veterinary medicine at all.
And it is a problem.

You know, I'm not sure this has any relevance to the conversation at all, but I have a friend now who came in yesterday from San Antonio with her little whatever the dog is that is 13 years old, fell off a bed, broke its disc, I guess it was, in the vertebra, was paralyzed, brought the dog in for care, concern, and treatment, and so forth, and probably she spent the weekend here
We were out of town.
Now she's going to spend four or five more days here.
I don't know how much money they're going to spend on that dog, but that is, in my mind, a classic example of a new kind of decision regarding treatment of animals.
It's technology availability.
They now have the ability to have them.
But she has the money to spend on that dog, and money is no object.
And money was the object.
You just don't do that.

That's one of the things that Elmo referred to when he brought up about food animal medicine, that many times they'll come to you and you give them an estimate on it, and economically they'll go over to the sale or they'll go to the slaughter plant.
That's right.
And you don't get anything.
Maybe you get a fee for telling them what to do, but there are a lot of those things that you just price yourself out of the market.
I could remember a guy having a head for cesarean for $20.
And he said, hell, I ain't going to spend that kind of money.
He said, no, this shit refers.
I said, well, if you've got two $20 bills in your pocket and you lose one, do you take the other one out and throw it away?
You've got a chance to recoup some of your funds.
There was an old boy who castrated horses named Pruitt in Fort Worth.
And he came out and set up an elaborate practice.
And he got $65 for horse castration.
Everybody else was getting $15.
This was in the late 40s, early 50s.
He didn't castrate many horses, but he made plenty of money when he did.
But there's quite a difference in establishing fees with individual practices.
And people, you call them at your clients.
I can remember an old lady drove up to the Cadillac with a black cat.
She liked for the cat to call the veterinarian by his first name.
And she'd been going to somebody and he said, look, I'm better for that damn cat calling me Joe.
And she came to see me.
There wasn't anything wrong with the cat.
She didn't mind paying $10 for me to rub the cat and tell him that this is Uncle Charlie and all that.
You know, we'll have that.
It's my estimate of good business.
Yeah.
And you deal with the people.
I've worked with this a lot.
The practitioner's out there dealing with it.
The client is the person, not the animal, particularly.
I can recall a man who was in the printing business, named Hodgkins, had a printing deal there in Arlington.
He went in the Charolais business, and I went out to Dee Horns from Gattle for him.
He had about, I think it was five young bulls there.

and he wanted the horns blocked you know it was routine to just chop those suckers off and treat them and i spent considerable time blocking the corneal nerves and cutting them off and an additional figure for each i don't give a damn what it costs i don't want to hurt them yeah so you know you've got the people that really put them in it's a change and that that kind of that part of the world is changing oh yeah the way you know
attitude toward animals, and this animal rights thing, and that's going to impact on you somehow, and I don't know how, or maybe it is already, but that's a strange thing to have to deal with.
Well, they're radical thinkers.
They have some points well taken, but it's the nuts that are taking the points.
You can deal with a rational person.
and correct some of those things, which I agree with.
We've got some things in the livestock industry and among veterinarians.
I want to give you some other names here.
Okay, good.
Thank you.
We're about ready to close it all.
I've got a question for you.
Have you ever been to the Hill College Confederate exhibit up there?
No.
I want you to go.
I promise you.
This is run by Colonel Simpson.
Yeah, I know Simpson.
Yeah, yeah.
You know, I've been, my wife and I went by there and it was closed.
So I went the other day.
